WEBVTT

00:22.850 --> 00:25.036
Good to see you.

00:25.076 --> 00:27.403
What a gift to be here.

00:27.443 --> 00:34.002
Thanks, Kyle and I have been encouraged by the ministry of the porch for a very, very long time.

00:34.146 --> 00:36.550
surreal for me to get to be here.

00:36.691 --> 00:38.073
I know you're here all the time.

00:38.834 --> 00:45.467
I'm sure you know how amazing it is that you get to be a part of this, but what God is doing in and through this ministry is incredible.

00:45.487 --> 00:48.372
So from Atlanta to you, thank you.

00:48.412 --> 00:51.277
And thanks for having me here tonight, Colin, thanks for having me.

00:51.437 --> 00:53.601
I love listening to Colin preach.

00:53.621 --> 00:55.064
I love listening to TA preach.

00:55.084 --> 00:58.450
It's not really fair that they're at the same church, but

00:58.562 --> 01:01.706
It's a real gift to be here, and I'm so excited about the message.

01:02.186 --> 01:05.190
I believe the Lord's given me for us tonight.

01:05.210 --> 01:06.872
I want to introduce you just a little bit.

01:06.892 --> 01:10.877
I know you don't need to know everything about me, but just a little bit since this is my first time here.

01:11.358 --> 01:12.579
This is a picture of my family.

01:14.221 --> 01:18.827
My wife and I have been married for just over 10 years, and these are our three girls.

01:19.368 --> 01:21.570
The oldest on the bottom left is Mercy.

01:21.610 --> 01:24.594
The blonde is Ember.

01:24.738 --> 01:27.123
And Charlie is our baby.

01:27.203 --> 01:28.746
Mercy is the typical firstborn.

01:29.287 --> 01:32.754
She asks for extra homework and has never broken a rule in her life.

01:33.916 --> 01:39.828
Ember, we're not sure if she's going to run a very large company one day or be incarcerated.

01:39.888 --> 01:40.850
Time will tell.

01:40.994 --> 01:44.221
And then Charlie is just happy to be alive.

01:44.281 --> 01:52.880
You know, third kid never had a bad day in her life, but it is, it's crazy how much joy they bring to my life.

01:52.920 --> 01:54.243
So love them a lot.

01:54.403 --> 01:56.909
I'm part of Passion City Church in Atlanta, Georgia.

01:56.969 --> 02:01.298
Been on team there for over 12 years, currently serving as the teaching pastor.

02:01.506 --> 02:06.401
And I'm so grateful that the Lord has invited me into what he's doing.

02:06.562 --> 02:15.730
So it's not the message tonight, but if I can just put a message before the message, the message would be God's plans for your life are so much better than your plans for your life.

02:16.354 --> 02:18.478
And I hope you believe that to be true.

02:18.959 --> 02:21.623
I've loved journeying along these last few weeks.

02:22.004 --> 02:22.845
It had been amazing.

02:22.885 --> 02:28.495
As you've been talking about mental health and health and perspective and navigating all that.

02:28.555 --> 02:41.618
And as I felt what the Lord was putting on my heart to share tonight, it was kind of beautiful how I think these things belong together because the title of the message tonight is you should get your hopes up.

02:42.786 --> 02:44.128
Can you just tell your neighbor that?

02:44.449 --> 02:46.171
Tell him, say, you should get your hopes up.

02:48.354 --> 02:49.897
And here's what I want you to understand.

02:50.097 --> 02:52.521
And I believe this with all of my heart.

02:53.242 --> 03:00.673
I believe that our hopes and our hope are inextricably linked together.

03:01.314 --> 03:05.861
That our hopes and our hope are part of the same conversation.

03:05.881 --> 03:09.266
Maybe you've heard it said before, you can go 40 days without food.

03:11.042 --> 03:11.603
That's pretty wild.

03:11.744 --> 03:13.688
I don't know if I really could or not, but apparently you can.

03:14.269 --> 03:15.953
You can go four days without water.

03:17.255 --> 03:22.968
You can go four minutes without air, but you can't go four seconds without hope.

03:24.010 --> 03:27.858
And I know when we talk about hope, there's immediately this thing that happens in us.

03:28.802 --> 03:37.936
Some of us chalk hope up to this ethereal, touchy feeling belongs on a self-help aisle of the bookstore.

03:37.996 --> 03:44.005
But what I'm hoping the Lord will open our eyes to see today is hope is what we have as the people of God.

03:44.305 --> 03:46.949
Hope is not just blind optimism.

03:47.050 --> 03:48.712
It is gritty theology.

03:48.792 --> 03:55.282
We are meant to display to the world a sure and confident hope.

03:56.194 --> 04:03.724
And so if we are people who belong to the God of hope, then we should get our hopes up.

04:04.866 --> 04:06.568
You should get your hopes up.

04:06.709 --> 04:08.431
I don't know how your hope is doing right now.

04:08.932 --> 04:13.218
I don't know if you feel hopeful and you feel confident about what the future holds for you.

04:13.238 --> 04:21.349
I don't know if you've got all kinds of, you know, like fog in front of you and you're going, I don't know, man, I don't know if what's in front of me is good or not.

04:21.769 --> 04:25.074
I want to say to you on the authority of God's word today,

04:25.218 --> 04:31.405
Not a self-help message, but from his word today, you should get your hopes.

04:32.286 --> 04:34.388
God has great things in store for you.

04:35.349 --> 04:40.294
He has given great purpose to your life and his plans for you are good.

04:40.314 --> 04:41.255
Do you believe that?

04:41.796 --> 04:43.318
I'm not saying they're gonna be easy.

04:43.358 --> 04:45.080
I'm not saying they're gonna be comfortable.

04:45.100 --> 04:48.724
I'm not saying you're gonna get the internship and you're gonna get the job and you're gonna get the girl and you're gonna get everything.

04:48.744 --> 04:49.504
That's not what I'm saying.

04:49.785 --> 04:50.986
I'm saying they're good.

04:51.146 --> 04:53.028
His plans for you are good.

04:53.068 --> 04:54.610
Do you believe that?

04:55.522 --> 05:08.695
And as the people of God, we are meant to live with this expectation and eagerness and anticipation that as I survey the landscape or even as I look at my own life, oftentimes I don't have.

05:11.217 --> 05:16.002
Have you ever gotten your hopes up only to be disappointed?

05:18.024 --> 05:19.225
That's not a good feeling, is it?

05:20.647 --> 05:22.308
Yesterday, this is kind of crazy.

05:22.368 --> 05:24.050
In Atlanta, Georgia, it was snowing.

05:26.114 --> 05:28.858
Look it up, you all think I'm lying, look it up, it was snowing.

05:29.078 --> 05:33.685
Now I'm not talking about like we were sledding, but I'm saying there was snow that came down from the sky yesterday in Atlanta, Georgia.

05:33.986 --> 05:42.178
And when we picked our kids up from school, there was like snow flurries happening and they had all the plants.

05:42.198 --> 05:55.858
We're gonna cancel school tomorrow, we're gonna go sledding, we're gonna do all the stuff we've seen in all the movies, and growing up in Atlanta, Georgia, probably similar if you grew up in Dallas, Texas, the idea of snow is a constant topic of getting your hopes up,

05:56.610 --> 05:57.915
only to be disappointed.

05:58.677 --> 06:04.919
You're going to go to school tomorrow and you ain't going to be able to sled because you live in Dallas, Texas or Atlanta, Georgia.

06:05.581 --> 06:06.364
But it's a hard thing.

06:06.404 --> 06:08.050
I remember this summer.

06:08.194 --> 06:13.699
the girls were wanting to go to the pool constantly, you know, and we had a month where it felt like it rained every single day.

06:13.979 --> 06:17.782
And we'd be at the dinner table and they would say to me like, Daddy, can we please go to the pool tomorrow?

06:17.982 --> 06:19.123
Can we please go to the pool tomorrow?

06:19.384 --> 06:24.448
And I was kind of like conflicted because I wanted to say to them, of course we can go to the pool tomorrow.

06:24.468 --> 06:27.591
But I also knew that the forecast was like 100% chance of rain.

06:27.871 --> 06:29.893
And so I would just like try to be a good dad.

06:29.913 --> 06:32.655
I'm like, yeah, okay, yeah, we can go to the pool tomorrow.

06:32.675 --> 06:38.180
And then the next morning at breakfast, you know, I'm having breakfast with two girls in Moana bathing suits.

06:38.160 --> 06:44.769
They're just ready to go to the pool, and it's pouring down rain outside, and I just would watch their faces kind of collapse.

06:45.210 --> 06:51.118
It's not a fun thing to get your hopes up only to be disappointed.

06:52.320 --> 06:59.570
Maybe it's something like a sports team that you thought was going to be good, and then they were like they always were.

07:00.034 --> 07:09.587
College application, you thought you were gonna get into a certain school, you had a plan for your life, but instead of an acceptance letter, you got a rejection letter and your hopes got up and then you got crushed.

07:11.389 --> 07:16.276
Maybe you experienced with a relationship, somebody that told you one thing and then did a different thing.

07:17.578 --> 07:24.006
Maybe you experienced with a parent, somebody who committed to your family and you thought they would always be there and then all of a sudden they just up and left.

07:24.667 --> 07:29.874
And you got your hopes up for what life would be like, only to be disappointed and crushed.

07:30.530 --> 07:31.831
or maybe for you it was a career.

07:31.891 --> 07:44.686
For me, I spent 20 years of my life thinking I was gonna do one thing with my life, play a game for the rest of my life, only for injury to come and a doctor to tell me I could never play the game again, and my hopes were up, and in 30 seconds, they came crashing down.

07:45.887 --> 07:50.272
I remember when my wife and I were buying our first house, this is not a fun process.

07:51.153 --> 07:55.518
It's less fun now, because the interest rates are like 10%, but it wasn't fun when I bought a house either.

07:55.558 --> 07:59.602
And I can remember we went to the first house with our real estate agent,

07:59.682 --> 08:01.965
And, you know, we walked in and it was amazing.

08:02.045 --> 08:04.146
I mean, it was tiny, like, you know, it was like...

08:04.770 --> 08:09.616
800 square feet and we walked in and it looked like Chip and Joanna had just been there.

08:09.896 --> 08:16.725
There was ship lap everywhere like on every wall, you know, and we're walking around and my newlywed wife and me and we're like, this is what this room's going to be.

08:16.765 --> 08:18.447
And this is what this room's going to be.

08:18.487 --> 08:20.749
And, you know, that's like all the rooms and it's going to be awesome.

08:21.230 --> 08:23.172
And we went out and I'm not kidding you.

08:23.212 --> 08:24.174
I have a picture on my phone.

08:24.354 --> 08:25.595
We went out into the driveway.

08:25.796 --> 08:28.499
We held hands and we were like, this is going to be so amazing.

08:28.579 --> 08:31.122
And in our minds, we had already moved into the house.

08:32.354 --> 08:38.000
And let me just pre-warn you, if you haven't bought a house yet, you ain't going to get the first house you look at.

08:38.981 --> 08:49.512
Because our real estate agent called us a few hours later and said, hey, somebody paid all cash for the house and they bought it at $100,000 over asking price.

08:50.313 --> 08:54.818
And I was like, who are all these rich jokers with the $100,000 cash?

08:56.800 --> 08:59.383
And we went into the next house.

08:59.403 --> 09:02.226
And our hopes were high, but not as high as the first house.

09:02.850 --> 09:04.612
And then we went into the next one and didn't get it.

09:05.112 --> 09:06.834
And then we went into the next one and didn't get it.

09:07.335 --> 09:09.117
And then we went into the next one and didn't get it.

09:09.798 --> 09:23.753
And every single time we walked into a new house, even if we loved the house, as a way of protecting ourselves from disappointment, we refused to get our hopes up.

09:26.075 --> 09:32.402
And I am convinced there are many of us in this room who are living life like that.

09:33.826 --> 09:39.276
Somehow, at some turn in life, you got your hopes up and you got disappointed.

09:40.298 --> 09:52.462
And as a way of self-preservation, as a way of not having to navigate through the storms of life, you've just refused to allow your hopes to get up for anything.

09:54.285 --> 09:56.690
But God has a different plan for your life.

09:57.090 --> 10:04.259
as people who belong to Christ, as people who are bought by His blood, as people who belong as sons and daughters of the God of hope.

10:04.640 --> 10:09.185
We are meant to live with confident expectation.

10:10.667 --> 10:13.671
So I came to Dallas tonight to ask you a simple question.

10:14.592 --> 10:15.253
How's your hope?

10:18.277 --> 10:19.859
How's your hope?

10:19.879 --> 10:22.482
And for those of you that are barely hanging on today,

10:22.978 --> 10:33.353
The writer of Hebrews tells us that we can have an unshakeable hope as an anchor for your soul, firm, and secure.

10:33.833 --> 10:35.115
That's Hebrews chapter six.

10:35.416 --> 10:41.144
What would it look like in your life if you had a hope that was firm and secure?

10:41.484 --> 10:43.688
Not fragile, but firm.

10:43.728 --> 10:51.058
Not shifting based on the circumstances of life, but secure.

10:51.554 --> 10:54.899
based on the fact that you belong to the king of kings.

10:55.841 --> 10:59.827
And what I wanna do for a few minutes is look at Romans chapter 15.

11:00.368 --> 11:05.936
We're gonna read 13 verses, but we're gonna spend almost our entire time in just one verse.

11:06.817 --> 11:10.443
The last verse, the benediction of Romans chapter 15.

11:10.723 --> 11:15.791
This is a section that Charles Spurgeon called one of the richest passages in the entire word of God.

11:16.512 --> 11:20.178
So if you have your Bible, I invite you to turn to Romans chapter 15

11:20.386 --> 11:22.428
I'm gonna begin reading in verse one.

11:23.529 --> 11:25.271
I think it's important that we see the context.

11:25.291 --> 11:28.875
It's why we're gonna read the first few verses together.

11:29.936 --> 11:41.128
It says, each of us should please our neighbors for their good to build them up.

11:41.769 --> 11:50.098
For even Christ did not please himself, but as it is written, the insults of those who insult you have fallen on me.

11:50.690 --> 11:52.953
Verse four would be a great verse for you to underline.

11:52.973 --> 11:53.814
We'll come back to this.

11:54.235 --> 12:10.518
For everything that was written in the past was written to teach us so that through the endurance taught in the scriptures and the encouragement that they provide, we might have, can you say the word with me?

12:12.221 --> 12:14.604
Okay, that was great, kinda.

12:15.886 --> 12:18.610
If we read the word hope, let's all say it together.

12:19.330 --> 12:23.476
encouragement they provide, we might have hope.

12:24.218 --> 12:43.507
May the God who gives endurance and encouragement give you the same attitude of mind towards each other that Christ Jesus had, so that with one mind and one voice, you may glorify the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, except one another then, just as Christ has accepted you in order to bring praise to God.

12:43.888 --> 12:47.794
For I tell you that Christ has become a servant of the Jews on behalf of God's truth.

12:47.970 --> 12:56.238
so that the promises made to the patriarchs might be confirmed, and moreover, that the Gentiles might glorify God for his mercy, as it is written.

12:56.558 --> 12:58.961
Therefore, I will praise you among the Gentiles.

12:59.301 --> 13:02.204
I will sing the praises of your name, verse 10.

13:02.504 --> 13:06.368
Again, it says, rejoice you Gentiles with his people, verse 11.

13:06.488 --> 13:11.653
And again, praise the Lord, all you Gentiles, let all the peoples extol him.

13:11.834 --> 13:16.338
And again, Isaiah says, the root of Jesse will spring up.

13:17.410 --> 13:26.519
And one who will arise to rule over the nations, in him the Gentiles will hope.

13:27.360 --> 13:29.322
Verse 13, pay attention closely.

13:29.362 --> 13:31.504
This is our verse for the rest of our time together.

13:32.164 --> 13:46.258
May the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace as you trust in him so that you may overflow with hope by the power of the Holy Spirit.

13:47.298 --> 13:47.819
Amen.

13:48.980 --> 13:50.401
What a verse.

13:51.823 --> 13:52.844
Look at that verse.

13:52.864 --> 14:03.395
May the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace as you trust in him so that you may overflow with hope by the power of the Holy Spirit.

14:03.415 --> 14:05.197
Or the ESV translates it this way.

14:05.417 --> 14:14.066
May the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace in believing so that by the power of the Spirit you may abound in hope.

14:14.722 --> 14:22.430
This is really like the exclamation point at the end of 15 chapters of brilliant doctrine from Paul.

14:23.091 --> 14:25.374
It's really the end of his teaching in Romans.

14:25.494 --> 14:30.419
After this, you pretty much just have a few final remarks and final greetings to a few people.

14:30.439 --> 14:44.274
So the crescendo of the book of Romans ends with this exclamation point that we should, as people who belong to the king, live lives that overflow with hope.

14:45.250 --> 14:46.511
I want you to see a few things.

14:46.632 --> 14:48.454
Number one, if you're taking notes, write this down.

14:48.874 --> 14:52.838
God is the only true source of hope.

14:54.480 --> 14:55.381
And you see it in the text.

14:55.662 --> 14:59.025
Paul says here, the God of hope.

14:59.846 --> 15:02.329
So maybe it would be helpful to try and define hope.

15:02.749 --> 15:10.558
Webster defines hope as a desire accompanied by expectation of or belief in its fulfillment.

15:10.578 --> 15:14.162
It is to want something to happen.

15:14.722 --> 15:16.624
That's how Webster defines hope.

15:16.905 --> 15:21.150
But for the believer, can I encourage you, hoping is not wishing.

15:22.291 --> 15:25.815
Biblical hope is way more than a simple wish.

15:26.256 --> 15:34.906
It entails certainty based on God's demonstration of faithfulness in the past and confidence that he will be faithful in the future.

15:35.867 --> 15:39.492
Our hope as believers is not blind to optimism.

15:39.612 --> 15:41.554
It is calculated faith.

15:41.890 --> 15:42.190
Right?

15:42.711 --> 15:45.034
Optimism is psychological.

15:45.394 --> 15:48.037
Biblical hope is theological.

15:49.019 --> 15:51.041
Optimism counts up the odds.

15:51.862 --> 15:58.110
Biblical hope counts on and in the God of hope.

15:59.071 --> 16:00.552
I love how John Piper says this.

16:00.653 --> 16:05.518
He says, biblical hope is biblical faith in the future tense.

16:06.640 --> 16:07.301
Don't you love that?

16:08.061 --> 16:11.826
Hope is the result of trusting

16:12.162 --> 16:13.544
in God.

16:13.564 --> 16:16.407
So Paul says, may the God of hope.

16:16.427 --> 16:22.254
Now, this doesn't mean God of hope like that he's a God that has hope for the future.

16:22.895 --> 16:24.317
I have a hope for God.

16:24.337 --> 16:25.278
That's not what Paul's saying.

16:26.159 --> 16:26.920
God's omniscient.

16:28.001 --> 16:31.586
He knows how everything's going to work out tomorrow and the next day and the next day and the next day and the next day.

16:31.826 --> 16:32.807
He's never been surprised.

16:33.028 --> 16:34.089
He's never Googled anything.

16:34.289 --> 16:35.671
He's never been informed of anything.

16:35.871 --> 16:36.652
He knows everything.

16:36.812 --> 16:38.354
It's a prerequisite for being God.

16:39.650 --> 16:42.333
So he doesn't have to be hopeful for tomorrow, because he's God.

16:42.934 --> 16:45.037
So it's not that he's a hopeful God.

16:45.057 --> 16:46.599
So what's Paul trying to say here?

16:47.260 --> 16:50.504
Well, it says that he's the God of hope.

16:50.524 --> 16:56.652
And I know many of you won't care about this, but when I was in seminary, we were taught that this is a genitive of product.

16:57.373 --> 16:59.656
That does something for any of the nerds in the room today.

17:00.177 --> 17:07.346
And in seminary, what I was taught the best way to understand a general of product is to put which or who produces in its place.

17:07.682 --> 17:10.246
And when you do that, this starts to make a little bit of sense.

17:10.566 --> 17:14.552
So may the God who produces hope.

17:15.012 --> 17:15.473
Do you see it?

17:15.913 --> 17:17.075
He's the source.

17:17.275 --> 17:19.478
He is the only true source.

17:19.659 --> 17:20.920
He produces hope.

17:21.141 --> 17:23.204
He is the fountain of hope.

17:23.304 --> 17:25.146
This is our God.

17:26.969 --> 17:36.562
And yet, all throughout the pages of this book and all throughout the years of your life and all throughout the years of my life,

17:37.122 --> 17:43.149
We have looked to a million other sources for hope, haven't we?

17:44.791 --> 17:45.852
In fact, I'm convinced.

17:47.414 --> 17:58.667
I'm convinced that many of us feel hopeless because we have hoped in less than the God of hope.

18:02.611 --> 18:05.074
Hope is the result of trusting in God.

18:06.146 --> 18:11.915
And yet we have trusted in so many other things and it's crippling our hope and it's crippling our health.

18:12.896 --> 18:15.380
The CDC released some data in 2023.

18:16.161 --> 18:17.083
That was pretty alarming.

18:17.483 --> 18:25.435
Stated that 40% of American teenagers reported persistent feelings of sadness or hopelessness.

18:28.259 --> 18:35.250
And I would suggest that many of them and many of us feel hopeless because we have settled for hoping in less.

18:35.906 --> 18:36.587
than the God of hope.

18:37.608 --> 18:39.010
And we see this all throughout the Scripture.

18:39.411 --> 18:40.532
You see it in the Old Testament.

18:40.732 --> 18:48.122
Jeremiah, known as the weeping prophet in Jeremiah chapter 2, verses 11 through 13, it says, has a nation ever changed its gods?

18:48.463 --> 18:50.806
Little G, yet they are not gods at all.

18:51.447 --> 18:55.192
But my people have exchanged their glorious God for worthless idols.

18:55.852 --> 19:00.018
He says, be appalled at this, you heavens, and shudder with great whore declares the Lord.

19:00.354 --> 19:02.738
My people have committed two sins.

19:03.019 --> 19:13.717
They have forsaken me, the spring of living water, and they have dug for themselves their own cisterns, broken cisterns that cannot hold water.

19:14.418 --> 19:16.602
So I want you to see the picture of what's happening here.

19:17.183 --> 19:26.098
A cistern was like this man-made, pear-shaped, normally deep hole

19:26.242 --> 19:38.198
with plaster and it would be like cut down into the rocks either in a community or sometimes in a wealthy family right outside of their home and it was used to store water from the rain.

19:40.000 --> 19:50.595
And so what the people were doing, the people who had depended on God time and time again, year after year after year, he would bring the rain which was a sign of blessing and provide for his people.

19:50.855 --> 19:56.082
And yet at some point the people said, you know what, let's dig a hole.

19:57.634 --> 20:07.667
And let's put some plaster in it and let's store up the rainwater just in case, just in case the rain cuts off tomorrow.

20:09.028 --> 20:11.171
We will have saved up enough for ourselves today.

20:13.053 --> 20:14.715
Let's just have a backup plan.

20:15.677 --> 20:16.998
We'll still believe in God.

20:17.659 --> 20:26.290
We'll still trust them for the rain, but just so we have a plan B, let's build a sister and out back.

20:29.186 --> 20:30.047
I know what that's like.

20:31.529 --> 20:33.112
I would get so many of you know what that's like.

20:35.896 --> 20:38.560
I know when to raise my hands in worship, when to pat my chest.

20:38.620 --> 20:39.822
I know how to sing all the songs.

20:39.842 --> 20:41.244
I know my scripture.

20:41.304 --> 20:43.207
I'm in church every time the doors are open.

20:43.247 --> 20:44.689
I know how to do all the Christian thing.

